nterpretations of these modernist authors to show how each presents his own poetics as a self-conscious departure from the modern antisemitic imaginary.Levi claims that, just as antisemites once feared their own contamination by a mobile, polluting Jewish spirit, so too much of postwar thought remains governed by the fear that it might be contaminated by the spirit of antisemitism. Thus he argues for the need to confront and work through our own fantasies and projections-not only about the figure of the Jew but also about that of the antisemite.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAntisemitism. 0aArt criticism. 0aModernism (Art) 0aModernism (Art). 4aCulture. 4aFascism. 4aHolocaust Studies. 4aJames Joyce. 4aJewification. 4aJews and the arts. 4aJudaization. 4aMax Nordau. 4aNazi art policy. 4aNazism. 4aRichard Wagner. 4aSamuel Beckett. 4aTheodor W. Adorno. 4aWyndham Lewis. 4aanti-semitism. 4afascism and the arts. 4amodernism. 4amodernity. 4athe arts. 4athe avant-garde. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082325508540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823255085423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823255085.jpg  a978-3-11-070729-8  FUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK